%N A391972 a(n) = 1 if n=1 or a(n-1) is prime; a(n) = a(n-1) + i otherwise, where i = n - r and r is the number of occurrences of 1 among terms a(1) to a(n-1).
%C A391972 Runs of growth from 1 up to a prime where each term adds +i for successive i = 1,2,3,... and those increments continue in each run.
%C A391972 During a "reset" from a prime back to 1, i does not increase. Thus, i only increases within runs so that i is smaller than n by the number of occurrences of 1 per the formula below.
%C A391972 The graph forms several near-linear lines. It appears that the distribution of "resets" to 1 doesn't diminish as the sequence progresses.
